25|$|Hypotenuse-Leg (HL) Theorem: The <b>hypotenuse</b> {{and a leg}} in a right {{triangle}} have the same length as those in another {{right triangle}}. This is also called RHS (right-angle, <b>hypotenuse,</b> side).|$|E
25|$|Recall {{that the}} square of an even number is even and {{the square of}} an odd number is odd. So if {{the square of the}} <b>hypotenuse</b> is even the <b>hypotenuse</b> is even as well.|$|E
25|$|There exist {{infinitely}} many primitive Pythagorean triples {{in which}} the <b>hypotenuse</b> and the longer of the two legs differ by exactly two. Generalization: For every integer k > 0, there exist infinitely many primitive Pythagorean triples {{in which the}} <b>hypotenuse</b> and the odd leg differ by 2k2.|$|E
